1
00:00:00,250 --> 00:00:05,557
Well, I think, I don't know, I'm only going by what I hear.

2
00:00:05,979 --> 00:00:10,766
I mean, I don't know myself about the position of therapy at some point.

3
00:00:10,846 --> 00:00:21,263
But the general feeling was that I was getting from people was that therapy was very good at getting people in touch with their stuff.

4
00:00:22,086 --> 00:00:23,910
but didn't quite know what to do with it when it was up.

5
00:00:24,591 --> 00:00:25,431
That's the, you know.

6
00:00:26,713 --> 00:00:30,559
And it was through research, wasn't it, by John Teasdale here in Cambridge.

7
00:00:31,801 --> 00:00:37,369
And, of course, Kabat-Zinn, bringing it to pain management, depression, anxiety.

8
00:00:37,750 --> 00:00:45,322
I mean, according to John, it was something like a 90% success of mindfulness and panic.

9
00:00:47,145 --> 00:00:50,710
Of not going back into panic, you know, fears to the bitter end.

10
00:00:52,731 --> 00:01:02,082
And it's really understanding what the Buddha means by dukkha, by suffering.

11
00:01:02,823 --> 00:01:08,188
And I think once we're clear on that, you can see the role of mindfulness in undermining suffering.

12
00:01:08,250 --> 00:01:16,679
It's just, it's pretty, you know, it's there in the, I mean, he puts it in the Second Noble Truth, see?

13
00:01:16,698 --> 00:01:20,382
I mean, the first is just basic statement that there is this dukkha.

14
00:01:20,644 --> 00:01:21,944
We'll define that in a minute.

15
00:01:22,432 --> 00:01:24,713
And the second one is the cause of it, which is desire.

16
00:01:26,015 --> 00:01:28,076
And the third one is very hopeful, there is an end to it.

17
00:01:29,239 --> 00:01:32,061
And the fourth, of course, is the path leading to it, the actual practice.

18
00:01:33,462 --> 00:01:35,765
So what does he mean by this word dukkha?

19
00:01:35,825 --> 00:01:37,426
It translates as hard to bear.

20
00:01:38,968 --> 00:01:44,132
But what he's referring to are three types, as he lists them.

21
00:01:44,753 --> 00:01:50,599
One is the suffering caused by attachment to

22
00:01:51,186 --> 00:01:59,745
sensual pleasure the next one is an attachment to becoming and the next one is an attachment to annihilation

23
00:02:00,450 --> 00:02:11,123
So it's a case of separating out what you would call just the natural pain, for want of a better word, of being a human being.

24
00:02:11,884 --> 00:02:14,328
So just the physical pain.

25
00:02:14,868 --> 00:02:17,712
He wasn't as though he got rid of physical pain.

26
00:02:17,772 --> 00:02:21,698
He died very uncomfortably with some sort of gastroenteritis.

27
00:02:22,318 --> 00:02:26,644
And he once asked Ananda to take over his speech because his back was hurting.

28
00:02:26,894 --> 00:02:37,750
So whatever he means by dukkha, this suffering, he's not referring to physical pain as such.

29
00:02:37,770 --> 00:02:49,866
And he's not, in our state of non-enlightenment, you might say, he's not talking about the primary level of mental suffering.

30
00:02:49,887 --> 00:02:55,955
So when we feel, in an obvious way, when we feel depressed or anxious or something like that,

31
00:02:56,358 --> 00:03:00,508
there isn't actually any suffering there in his terminology.

32
00:03:01,248 --> 00:03:02,973
There is just this mental state.

33
00:03:03,694 --> 00:03:10,449
Now, to understand that, you have to go into his psychology, which he called dependent origination.

34
00:03:10,509 --> 00:03:11,633
It basically says that.

35
00:03:12,118 --> 00:03:16,965
Something arises dependent on something else, that's all.

36
00:03:16,985 --> 00:03:22,711
And therefore it doesn't have its own existence, it doesn't have its own reality base, you can say.

37
00:03:22,850 --> 00:03:25,274
Everything is interdependent, I'm sure you've heard that.

38
00:03:26,756 --> 00:03:28,457
The Buddha's gone on and on about that.

39
00:03:28,478 --> 00:03:33,424
This was turned into a sort of universal idea by Mahayana.

40
00:03:33,743 --> 00:03:40,692
But in the original teaching, you might say, the Buddha stayed very close to the human actual experience.

41
00:03:41,194 --> 00:03:45,141
He was very wary of turning anything into some sort of metaphysics.

42
00:03:46,243 --> 00:03:50,510
So he really, when you read the Theravada scriptures, he's right there with the human being.

43
00:03:51,353 --> 00:03:57,943
And what we experience, our personal experience within this globe of consciousness through which we experience the world.

44
00:03:58,784 --> 00:04:06,679
So, this problem of desire...

45
00:04:09,292 --> 00:04:12,137
We begin by what is our essential mistake.

46
00:04:12,157 --> 00:04:18,127
So the Buddha is saying that somehow we've made some mistake somewhere, which is often translated as a delusion.

47
00:04:19,370 --> 00:04:23,156
And this fundamental mistake is a mistake of relationship.

48
00:04:24,038 --> 00:04:30,591
The relationship is to seek happiness in a world that's not going to deliver happiness.

49
00:04:31,718 --> 00:04:34,541
if only by the fact that it just doesn't stay.

50
00:04:34,581 --> 00:04:36,184
It's always in a process of change.

51
00:04:36,665 --> 00:04:46,678
So as soon as you think you've got, you've entered into this heavenly place, in whatever way you might define that for yourself, it always moves on.

52
00:04:46,879 --> 00:04:47,759
It always comes to an end.

53
00:04:48,841 --> 00:04:53,627
So, you know, when you have a great party and somebody says, we must do this again, you know you're heading for disaster.

54
00:04:55,690 --> 00:04:56,713
Because the second time is never.

55
00:04:56,952 --> 00:04:57,814
It loses juice.

56
00:04:58,975 --> 00:05:01,218
So this idea of...

57
00:05:02,144 --> 00:05:30,699
seeking happiness in the wrong place so the fundamental position then is one of trying to seek this happiness in a world that's transient and doesn't deliver and the more you accumulate the more you feel safe so the more friends you have the more feeling of friendship you feel safe

58
00:05:31,067 --> 00:05:34,372
the more money you have in the bank, you feel safe.

59
00:05:34,752 --> 00:05:37,636
You're always moving back to this business of safety, you see.

60
00:05:37,656 --> 00:05:50,410
And that fundamental feeling of safety is resting upon a deep understanding somewhere within our being, for want of a better word, that we're not safe, that there is death.

61
00:05:52,372 --> 00:05:55,055
And so we cover that up by making something of life.

62
00:05:55,336 --> 00:06:00,822
So we move towards life and what it can give us, and we make ourselves feel safe.

63
00:06:01,391 --> 00:06:03,293
by all sorts of little mechanisms.

64
00:06:04,415 --> 00:06:11,826
Unfortunately, once we've accumulated this stuff, it has to be defended against marauders, you see, and against the government.

65
00:06:12,646 --> 00:06:19,815
So you have to build up a certain aversion, see, to get the energy to get rid of the enemy.

66
00:06:20,857 --> 00:06:24,581
If the enemy looms a little too large, well, you've got to run for it.

67
00:06:25,286 --> 00:06:46,805
So there's your three basic dispositions in life coming from this fundamental delusion or mistake about seeking happiness, real happiness, not transient happiness, real, permanent, meaningfulness, real, permanent, existential groundedness in the transient world.

68
00:06:47,343 --> 00:06:50,807
Business of acquisition, accumulation, aversion, and fear.

69
00:06:51,269 --> 00:06:54,834
So from these three dispositions, we move into every moment, right?

70
00:06:54,853 --> 00:06:55,954
It's always there underneath.

71
00:06:56,276 --> 00:07:00,060
It's not that every moment demands these things, but they're always there as potential.

72
00:07:00,721 --> 00:07:08,713
And we move into actions of speech, thought, thought in our head, you see, and then it moves out into speech and then into action.

73
00:07:09,334 --> 00:07:12,978
Once you've done that, you see, you've created something within yourself.

74
00:07:12,999 --> 00:07:15,122
You've created a conditioning, right?

75
00:07:15,658 --> 00:07:19,064
And it's these conditionings that are driving your destiny.

76
00:07:19,725 --> 00:07:44,079
So these conditionings that we built up unwittingly in childhood and in early, you know, up to teenage and places of that sort of age, and even beyond people who are not aware, who are not mindful, this compendium of habits is basically what we call our character, our personality.

77
00:07:44,430 --> 00:07:46,033
And it drives our destiny, you see.

78
00:07:46,593 --> 00:07:49,656
And it's only when we hit walls that we begin to question.

79
00:07:50,076 --> 00:07:51,718
Normally speaking, we blame everybody else.

80
00:07:51,738 --> 00:07:52,480
That's much easier.

81
00:07:52,660 --> 00:07:55,322
You know, society, parents, everybody, that fault.

82
00:07:56,463 --> 00:08:04,413
But slowly wake up that maybe this crash has come about because of a certain way that I'm behaving.

83
00:08:08,297 --> 00:08:12,781
When the Buddha was fully liberated, we say he had three knowledges.

84
00:08:12,922 --> 00:08:14,403
Three knowledges came to him.

85
00:08:14,586 --> 00:08:25,800
The first one was that he was completely, he'd come to the end of these, what he called defilements, these wrong ways of relating.

86
00:08:26,901 --> 00:08:31,627
There was nothing unwholesome in his heart.

87
00:08:32,227 --> 00:08:34,870
There was nothing unskillful in his thinking anymore.

88
00:08:36,493 --> 00:08:42,460
That had been completely taken away because of some deep delusion had been destroyed.

89
00:08:42,860 --> 00:08:43,902
We'll come to that in a minute.

90
00:08:44,471 --> 00:08:59,027
And then he had memories of all his past lives, and he saw that it was his ethical decisions which had moved him into hell realms, into hellish places, and then finally driven him to his liberation.

91
00:08:59,047 --> 00:09:08,756
And then he saw beings moving from one place to another, driven by this same cause of karma.

92
00:09:09,518 --> 00:09:13,922
So what he's saying there is that

93
00:09:14,947 --> 00:09:24,749
Our consciousness, for want of a better word, is in a process of relationship.

94
00:09:25,230 --> 00:09:29,438
So everything is to do with ethics, see?

95
00:09:29,578 --> 00:09:34,509
We in our time, we medicalize things, right?

96
00:09:35,047 --> 00:10:04,648
or you socialize things so you do things because your parents have done this to you and all that sort of stuff or you've got some sort of illness or something like that remember that our forebears would talk about being a bit off or got out the wrong side of bed or feeling heavy but now we talk about depression you see and it becomes a sort of mental dis-ease when you go to the east they don't they they they they physicalize it they embody it they say that they're feeling down or they're feeling heavy

97
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,605
but they don't turn it into a psychological thing, you see.

98
00:10:08,625 --> 00:10:14,793
So as soon as you turn it into a psychological problem, then it becomes, you have to move towards therapy.

99
00:10:14,812 --> 00:10:22,744
And in a sense, it takes away the personal responsibility we have for having constructed these mental states.

100
00:10:23,284 --> 00:10:24,846
That's the problem.

101
00:10:24,866 --> 00:10:30,214
So it's the personal responsibility of having constructed depression, anxiety.

102
00:10:30,193 --> 00:10:47,519
Now, the understanding is that when something comes towards us, either a physical pain, somebody hits me on the nose, or some anger from somebody, that somehow they're causing this reaction.

103
00:10:48,539 --> 00:10:50,722
That their anger is causing my anger.

104
00:10:51,303 --> 00:10:54,629
That this clout on the nose is causing my grief.

105
00:10:55,570 --> 00:10:58,293
And because I can't get my own back, I feel very depressed.

106
00:10:59,083 --> 00:11:07,004
I once went to a group that was a group for depressive, people suffering from depression.

107
00:11:07,024 --> 00:11:15,725
And we sat in a circle and everybody started telling everybody else how depressed they were, which was extraordinarily depressing.

108
00:11:16,971 --> 00:11:25,523
And then when we got round to one person who said he wasn't depressed, he was really happy, he was obviously up on a bit of a high, everybody looked very jealous and glum.

109
00:11:26,264 --> 00:11:31,870
And everything they said, well, I'll give you an example.

110
00:11:31,910 --> 00:11:40,701
The leader of the group said, a week ago or so or something like that, I tripped over the pavement and hurt myself.

111
00:11:42,104 --> 00:11:44,447
So I wrote to the council and asked for compensations.

112
00:11:45,743 --> 00:11:49,128
The council wrote back and said that it wasn't on.

113
00:11:49,168 --> 00:11:50,068
He wasn't going to get a penny.

114
00:11:51,010 --> 00:11:51,951
So he got very angry.

115
00:11:52,673 --> 00:11:55,437
And then he got depressed.

116
00:11:55,456 --> 00:11:58,761
And it was the council with this pavement that had caused this depression.

117
00:12:00,924 --> 00:12:06,332
Now, in the Buddhist psychology, that's not actually what's happening.

118
00:12:06,352 --> 00:12:10,798
What's happening is some information is coming towards us.

119
00:12:12,701 --> 00:12:14,804
And the reaction that we have to it

120
00:12:15,224 --> 00:12:20,850
The response, for want of a better word, reaction that we have to it, is actually coming from a different centre.

121
00:12:21,792 --> 00:12:24,455
It's not coming from this person.

122
00:12:25,336 --> 00:12:26,878
It's not coming from the pain on my nose.

123
00:12:28,039 --> 00:12:41,956
The reaction is pain on my nose, which I'm well aware of, and then inside me, coming from a different place, is this little being who's quite frightened because somebody's just hit them on the nose.

124
00:12:42,611 --> 00:12:46,434
And the way you respond to somebody hitting you on the nose is you get very angry, right?

125
00:12:46,755 --> 00:12:50,097
Unless they're very big, and then you run for it, see?

126
00:12:50,118 --> 00:12:56,663
And that's coming from this inner center of the heart, not from the bump on the nose, see?

127
00:12:56,683 --> 00:13:02,548
So when we get, these days, you know, a lot of people are suffering from this unemployment.

128
00:13:02,568 --> 00:13:12,197
Now, when you become unemployed, as I sort of remember it, there's a loss of your wealth, there's a loss of your status, there's an immediate...

129
00:13:12,261 --> 00:13:40,767
loss of your place right now that is that's bad enough as it were because you have to read you know reorganize yourself you might say but on top of that there's something else happens which is to become depressed about it so that's this inner reaction to a situation right and what mindfulness is drawing us to understand is that that isn't necessary

130
00:13:41,876 --> 00:13:43,519
That second part is not necessarily.

131
00:13:43,759 --> 00:13:46,081
So the Buddha always talks about these two darts.

132
00:13:46,221 --> 00:13:52,909
The first dart is just the pains and sorrows and woes of ordinary living on this planet.

133
00:13:53,730 --> 00:13:59,378
And the second one was completely self-manufactured as a relationship to what was happening.

134
00:14:00,019 --> 00:14:02,802
And that relationship is our ethical position.

135
00:14:03,543 --> 00:14:08,928
Either we're trying to accumulate something or we're trying to push it away or we're trying to run for it.

136
00:14:09,188 --> 00:14:09,990
That's a relationship.

137
00:14:10,029 --> 00:14:11,412
It's an ethical relationship.

138
00:14:12,201 --> 00:14:15,024
Now, the Buddha himself didn't have a brilliant time all the time.

139
00:14:15,265 --> 00:14:30,222
Towards the end of his life, I think he got quite worried because the two great kings who had been his great supporters, one was murdered by his son, and the other one died naturally, and the two sons who became kings didn't like him at all.

140
00:14:30,263 --> 00:14:37,070
In fact, one plotted with Devadatta, a dastardly fellow, who was a monk, and tried to kill him.

141
00:14:37,591 --> 00:14:38,412
I'm going to tell you the story, yeah?

142
00:14:38,797 --> 00:14:43,802
And the other prince, actually, he married into the Sakya family, his family.

143
00:14:44,081 --> 00:14:49,787
And because they thought he was of a lower caste, they gave, they secretly gave him a slave girl.

144
00:14:49,826 --> 00:14:51,249
I mean, you know, the untouchable.

145
00:14:52,068 --> 00:14:54,451
And when he found this out, of course, he was raging.

146
00:14:54,511 --> 00:14:58,816
And he got on his elephant with all his other elephants and started going to destroy the Sakyas.

147
00:14:59,275 --> 00:15:01,759
The Buddha turned up and said, you know, hey, what's going on here, is it?

148
00:15:02,698 --> 00:15:05,461
And he got a bit of sense and he got, and he rode back, you see.

149
00:15:05,745 --> 00:15:07,347
But after a while, he got into his heart again.

150
00:15:07,389 --> 00:15:09,191
He got on his elephant, and off he went again, you see.

151
00:15:09,211 --> 00:15:12,316
And the Buddha said, whoa, turned up and said, hey, what's happening, you see.

152
00:15:12,856 --> 00:15:13,758
So he said, okay.

153
00:15:13,778 --> 00:15:14,759
So he went back again, you see.

154
00:15:15,259 --> 00:15:18,926
Third time on his elephant, whoa, and the Buddha turns up, come on, he says, you know.

155
00:15:18,985 --> 00:15:19,687
So he turns back.

156
00:15:20,028 --> 00:15:22,191
The fourth time, the Buddha says, I can't do anything.

157
00:15:22,211 --> 00:15:22,532
That's it.

158
00:15:22,751 --> 00:15:23,472
He won't listen now.

159
00:15:24,053 --> 00:15:24,754
And, of course, he did.

160
00:15:25,014 --> 00:15:28,561
The Sakyas were, many of them were killed.

161
00:15:28,581 --> 00:15:30,724
They had to move their capital elsewhere.

162
00:15:31,447 --> 00:15:44,057
So these were very worrying times for him towards the end, and he obviously was concerned about the order, the support of the order, because, as you know, these religions grow because of temporal support.

163
00:15:45,198 --> 00:15:49,081
I mean, in China, for instance, whenever the emperor was Buddhist, you were away.

164
00:15:49,501 --> 00:15:51,004
When he wasn't, you ran for the hills.

165
00:15:51,803 --> 00:15:55,307
That's how they developed this kung fu, you see, sort of self-defense.

166
00:15:56,307 --> 00:15:58,649
In our rule as a monk, we can defend ourselves.

167
00:15:58,690 --> 00:15:59,770
You're not supposed to attack.

168
00:15:59,791 --> 00:16:01,032
You can definitely defend yourself.

169
00:16:01,315 --> 00:16:09,144
So that whole way of combat in which you're trying to use the other person's energy to undermine them, to destroy them, you know?

170
00:16:09,525 --> 00:16:14,371
And as they pass you by, it's a quick rabbit chop, you know?

171
00:16:14,392 --> 00:16:16,975
So it's... Just finish it off, you know, coup de grace.

172
00:16:16,995 --> 00:16:20,340
So... No, where was I?

173
00:16:20,399 --> 00:16:21,942
I go off on these tales and I forget where I am.

174
00:16:22,942 --> 00:16:29,530
So, yes, so we're still struggling with this word dukkha and how to deal with it and where mindfulness comes in.

175
00:16:29,551 --> 00:16:29,971
So...

176
00:16:30,475 --> 00:16:52,061
The Buddha's saying, you see, if you put your attention in between the original pain, whether it comes physically at you, like you bump your head and catch your finger in the door or something, or whether you put it within yourself as some old conditioning arises, some depression, some sadness, some guilt, some shame, you see.

177
00:16:52,081 --> 00:16:58,288
If you put your attention there, upon that object, you see, and you observe this

178
00:16:58,504 --> 00:17:28,038
relationship you have with it, of indulging it, see, indulging our depression, you know, I'm so depressed, I'm depressed, you know, all this self-hatred, you know, I'm terrible, I'm useless, nobody loves me, it's true, I'm horrible, things like that, and you're working, you're actually developing your, that particular conditioning by this indulgence, see, sort of a false humility, so by observing that reaction, you're cutting in between

179
00:17:28,255 --> 00:17:33,299
the original suffering or pain that's coming up, physical or mental, and this reaction.

180
00:17:34,401 --> 00:17:45,472
When this reaction falls away, you can stay with the original pain and you've discovered a sort of an equanimity with it, a non-reactive position.

181
00:17:46,133 --> 00:17:57,384
And when you do that, you find that this original pain, whether it's the pain in the nose, the physical thing, or something in the heart as a mental state, begins to evaporate.

182
00:17:58,089 --> 00:18:02,695
And if you do it long enough, you realize that actually there's some therapy going on.

183
00:18:02,715 --> 00:18:04,498
The heart's purifying itself.

184
00:18:04,637 --> 00:18:05,599
It's healing itself.

185
00:18:06,079 --> 00:18:07,863
You begin to realize you don't have to do anything.

186
00:18:09,305 --> 00:18:10,665
All you have to do is be aware of it.

187
00:18:10,726 --> 00:18:17,414
But that awareness demands a certain ability to bear with, to bear with the conditions.

188
00:18:18,172 --> 00:18:25,419
And what we also discover is that the heart cannot purify itself except into consciousness.

189
00:18:25,439 --> 00:18:34,886
And it will either do it as a felt emotional state or as a physical illness, psychosomatic illness.

190
00:18:34,906 --> 00:18:47,959
So this ability to cut in between the original given unfortunate state and the reaction to it is, you might say, the point of escape.

191
00:18:48,361 --> 00:18:49,301
That's how he would put it.

192
00:18:49,423 --> 00:18:50,364
There's the escape.

193
00:18:50,403 --> 00:18:51,325
The escape from what?

194
00:18:51,605 --> 00:18:54,450
The escape from further suffering and past suffering.

195
00:18:56,011 --> 00:18:58,494
The escape from suffering caused by the past.

196
00:18:59,636 --> 00:19:12,174
So when you realize the power of that mindfulness to be with suffering, then you obviously want to be there more and more.

197
00:19:27,088 --> 00:19:29,071
Tell them they'd be expelled if they make any noise.

198
00:19:32,436 --> 00:19:40,888
So this mindfulness that the Buddha's talking about.

199
00:19:40,929 --> 00:19:48,839
So there's your, that's mindfulness at its most obvious position in the Four Noble Truths is desire the cause of suffering.

200
00:19:48,861 --> 00:19:53,366
So remember desire here is the desire to accumulate, the desire to

201
00:19:53,666 --> 00:20:19,101
annihilates to get rid of what you don't want and the desire to run from fear you see so that you might say that that there if a person can see that in their depression in their anxiety in their rage in their revenge and all they can see that you see that they found an escape from suffering so

202
00:20:20,481 --> 00:20:26,752
You can see how it's very helpful in all these therapies to get a person to find that position within themselves.

203
00:20:28,315 --> 00:20:34,705
It's talked about as the objective observer, the objective feeler, or the one who knows, the one who experiences.

204
00:20:35,267 --> 00:20:44,261
So by objectifying what we experience, we find a sort of different place, something which is transcending consciousness.

205
00:20:44,663 --> 00:20:48,067
transcending what we would normally identify with.

206
00:20:48,087 --> 00:20:49,710
So what do we mean by transcending?

207
00:20:50,090 --> 00:20:53,796
We mean by transcending finding a different identity point.

208
00:20:55,238 --> 00:21:00,685
So when we are in the body, when we are the body, we are the body self.

209
00:21:01,006 --> 00:21:02,407
That's who I am.

210
00:21:03,328 --> 00:21:06,012
Children, that's where they live in their bodies, you know.

211
00:21:06,549 --> 00:21:09,054
They don't separate their emotions or thought life.

212
00:21:09,094 --> 00:21:11,578
They are their bodies in a very embodied way.

213
00:21:12,840 --> 00:21:16,226
We really can only get to that level by accident.

214
00:21:16,507 --> 00:21:22,978
If you trap your finger in a door, just for that one singular sweet moment, you are the body.

215
00:21:23,338 --> 00:21:25,942
And then you jump out of that and start kicking the door.

216
00:21:27,391 --> 00:21:31,237
So to be a body self, you know, you have to get into sort of high states.

217
00:21:31,257 --> 00:21:35,201
I mean, that's why, you know, people like these dangerous sports.

218
00:21:35,363 --> 00:21:42,573
Because just for that one moment, they are that experience of, you know, going through rapids or flying in the air or something.

219
00:21:46,117 --> 00:21:50,704
And when you identify with something so totally like that, you feel completely alive.

220
00:21:52,626 --> 00:21:54,710
In that moment of absorption, there's no you.

221
00:21:54,810 --> 00:21:55,811
There's just the action.

222
00:21:56,972 --> 00:22:00,397
So that's the paradox.

223
00:22:01,419 --> 00:22:04,183
When we're completely happy, we don't know it.

224
00:22:05,424 --> 00:22:09,892
And as soon as you bounce out of it, you've lost it.

225
00:22:09,912 --> 00:22:12,756
What you're aware of is the dregs of the happy state.

226
00:22:14,679 --> 00:22:16,961
This ability to absorb into something.

227
00:22:17,702 --> 00:22:25,815
We do it, many of us do it just at work, which we find interesting, and you're just absorbed into it.

228
00:22:26,233 --> 00:22:28,756
People have hobbies like gardening.

229
00:22:29,576 --> 00:22:30,438
Time passes.

230
00:22:31,838 --> 00:22:35,561
The garden's been done beautifully, but there's not been a sense of somebody doing it.

231
00:22:36,262 --> 00:22:38,244
So these are our happiest moments.

232
00:22:38,644 --> 00:22:43,509
And as soon as you jump out of it, then there's something that knows your happiness.

233
00:22:43,529 --> 00:22:45,692
You've lost that happiness in a way.

234
00:22:45,731 --> 00:22:46,711
You've objectified it.

235
00:22:48,013 --> 00:22:56,240
So coming out of the body and being aware of the body as something means that my identity isn't there.

236
00:22:57,502 --> 00:23:27,425
I mean my identity will soon re-establish itself if something is death threatening life threatening as soon as something threatens my life then I really become my body very quickly but I can actually find this other position of having a body without being one so when I'm looking at my hand you see there's something looking at the hand it's not in the hand

237
00:23:28,402 --> 00:23:29,903
So it becomes an object to me.

238
00:23:30,605 --> 00:23:31,605
That's a different relationship.

239
00:23:31,826 --> 00:23:33,327
I still own this hand.

240
00:23:33,749 --> 00:23:36,913
My relationship with this hand is different from my relationship to your hand.

241
00:23:38,015 --> 00:23:41,859
If you lost your hand, I'd be very compassionate.

242
00:23:41,880 --> 00:23:44,522
But if I lost my hand, I'd go berserk.

243
00:23:44,542 --> 00:23:45,203
That's the difference.

244
00:23:46,846 --> 00:23:51,652
So the next identity is, of course, emotions, you see.

245
00:23:52,553 --> 00:23:56,838
So I am happy, I am sad, and so on and so forth.

246
00:23:57,258 --> 00:23:59,561
That's an easy one for us to stay with.

247
00:24:00,123 --> 00:24:02,086
If it's a good one, we like it.

248
00:24:02,105 --> 00:24:06,192
If we don't, we tend to jump out of it and become aware of it.

249
00:24:08,675 --> 00:24:16,028
Only when you go into it completely do you find yourself becoming mentally ill or falling into an uncontrollable rage.

250
00:24:16,509 --> 00:24:20,555
So there's that point of identity that I am.

251
00:24:20,575 --> 00:24:22,438
If you say I am...

252
00:24:22,839 --> 00:24:27,967
In the identity, in that moment of identity, there is no I am, there is just the identity.

253
00:24:28,748 --> 00:24:31,613
There is just depression, just panic.

254
00:24:32,653 --> 00:24:37,601
In a panic situation, you just lose it, you just go for it, and then you wake up out of it.

255
00:24:43,509 --> 00:24:48,797
When you become aware of an emotional state, it's an object, isn't it?

256
00:24:49,080 --> 00:24:55,211
So there's something in us which is no longer identifying with the emotional state, though fully aware of it.

257
00:24:57,315 --> 00:25:01,240
And then there's the mental identity of thought.

258
00:25:01,461 --> 00:25:02,303
That's even easier.

259
00:25:02,584 --> 00:25:06,089
I mean, we'll go off on these thought trips anytime.

260
00:25:06,871 --> 00:25:08,933
And you just get lost in thought, you see.

261
00:25:08,953 --> 00:25:11,679
And then you wake up, and the thought's gone.

262
00:25:12,339 --> 00:25:15,325
In meditation sometimes...

263
00:25:15,777 --> 00:25:22,605
when this ability to remain as the observer is very acute, you can see thoughts arising and passing away.

264
00:25:22,705 --> 00:25:25,288
They don't develop because you're not in there to develop them.

265
00:25:25,669 --> 00:25:28,853
You can see a thought arising and passing away, like a neon light.

266
00:25:30,255 --> 00:25:42,830
So, you've got these three major identities, which you're pulling out of the body with its sensations, feelings, the heart with its emotions, moods, and the mind with its thoughts and images.

267
00:25:43,891 --> 00:25:46,276
And when you pull out of that, you've found a different identity.

268
00:25:46,695 --> 00:25:50,002
You're now the observer, the feeler, the knower.

269
00:25:50,022 --> 00:26:03,367
And that's the position of somebody who's being mindful in that mindful of, in this particular case with therapy, mindful of painful states, painful mental states.

270
00:26:09,592 --> 00:26:11,193
Now that isn't your final position.

271
00:26:11,394 --> 00:26:14,376
To be the observer is the observer, the feel and what not.

272
00:26:14,396 --> 00:26:15,499
It's not your final position.

273
00:26:16,078 --> 00:26:24,008
But the Buddha actually says those who are mindful like that are in the vicinity of, in the neighborhood of Nibbana.

274
00:26:25,670 --> 00:26:38,805
So when we're in that state, mainly in the sitting posture, and you find yourself acutely being this observer within all this body, mind and heart, usually the body has to be very still

275
00:26:39,207 --> 00:26:43,393
and the heart has to be very calm, and the mind has to be silent.

276
00:26:43,413 --> 00:26:46,557
And then there's this very acute sense of the observer, the feeler, you see.

277
00:26:47,178 --> 00:26:52,546
So when that comes to you, you see, after that experience, ask yourself, what was it like being there?

278
00:26:52,786 --> 00:26:54,588
What were the constituents of the observer?

279
00:27:00,477 --> 00:27:06,345
Because at that point, you see, there's the ability to discover what we really are,

280
00:27:06,847 --> 00:27:08,351
Which is something transcendent.

281
00:27:08,530 --> 00:27:12,117
So it's something which transcends all these identities.

282
00:27:12,920 --> 00:27:15,585
Even the identity of an observer, of a feeler.

283
00:27:17,548 --> 00:27:19,030
And that's what the Buddha is pointing to.

284
00:27:19,090 --> 00:27:30,071
So when he's teaching of not-self, it's just this way of saying everything that we experience, if you can objectify it, it can't be you.

285
00:27:30,945 --> 00:27:41,597
When you are aware of yourself as a self, as an observer, as a feeler, there's something that feels itself to be a self.

286
00:27:41,938 --> 00:27:43,579
So it can't be that because it's an object.

287
00:27:45,321 --> 00:27:48,444
So you're always moving, you're always taking a step backwards.

288
00:27:49,405 --> 00:27:54,731
And when you actually fall off the cliff of the self, that's it.

289
00:27:54,971 --> 00:27:58,556
That's when we realize who we really are.

290
00:27:58,576 --> 00:28:00,597
That's the transcendent point.

291
00:28:01,304 --> 00:28:05,347
And that's what the Buddha is referring to when he calls himself the Tathāgata.

292
00:28:05,367 --> 00:28:09,271
Tathāgata means, you know, arrive there or gone there.

293
00:28:09,811 --> 00:28:16,077
And its best translation is the transcendent one, the one who's transcended the psycho-physical world.

294
00:28:18,921 --> 00:28:30,011
So now, this mindfulness, when it comes to just ordinary problems of life, ordinary mental problems like anxiety and lots of stuff,

295
00:28:31,105 --> 00:28:42,636
What it does is, it allows the person to find that position where they are no longer making things worse by identifying with that emotional state.

296
00:28:44,298 --> 00:28:50,925
That's the desire, that's this business of either saying, I am depressed.

297
00:28:51,406 --> 00:28:55,590
As soon as you say, I am depressed, I am depressed, where's the escape?

298
00:28:58,994 --> 00:29:00,977
But as soon as you say, there's depression,

299
00:29:01,800 --> 00:29:03,423
There's an escape, isn't there?

300
00:29:03,443 --> 00:29:06,828
You can do something about it if it's there within yourself.

301
00:29:07,670 --> 00:29:11,336
But as soon as you say, I am, that's it.

302
00:29:11,355 --> 00:29:15,382
We're locked into a particular type of relationship, this identity with it.

303
00:29:16,042 --> 00:29:26,880
So the ability to maintain that mindfulness stops that identity, which is indulging it, which is actually making it worse,

304
00:29:27,535 --> 00:29:30,679
and allows the original state to manifest.

305
00:29:30,719 --> 00:29:43,717
And that's what's so difficult, is to be with these very painful mental states and just be with it in this calm way and feel them, experience them fully.

306
00:29:44,919 --> 00:29:49,546
And what you're doing is you're saying to your heart, manifest your turbulence.

307
00:29:50,226 --> 00:29:54,172
And it's in that manifestation that turbulence can exhaust itself.

308
00:29:54,653 --> 00:29:56,394
So that over a period of time,

309
00:29:56,746 --> 00:30:00,891
you begin to feel this alleviation of all this turmoil within the heart.

310
00:30:02,011 --> 00:30:03,453
Think 25 years.

311
00:30:04,094 --> 00:30:06,497
I wouldn't want to give you any false hope.

312
00:30:08,038 --> 00:30:14,865
So, this business of indulgence, how do we develop our mental states?

313
00:30:15,906 --> 00:30:17,108
We develop them through thought.

314
00:30:20,291 --> 00:30:26,179
It's through making up these constant stories that we're actually developing mental states.

315
00:30:26,902 --> 00:30:33,731
So the first thing is to know that the mind, if it's not under our control, is really working against us.

316
00:30:34,673 --> 00:30:44,028
So anxiety, remember, is really being anxious, 99% of the time, anxious about things that aren't going to happen.

317
00:30:46,510 --> 00:30:53,060
Because the mind here, in a state of fright, in a state of uncertainty, extends the future outwards.

318
00:30:53,699 --> 00:30:58,563
And it always builds up this tremendous fearful sort of storyline.

319
00:31:00,704 --> 00:31:04,088
The scenario of fear just extends itself.

320
00:31:04,648 --> 00:31:14,018
And that's completely unnecessary because if you come back into the moment, you see, and you feel the fear, and do it anyway, you all know the book, yeah?

321
00:31:14,038 --> 00:31:17,320
So you feel the fear, you see, and you're letting it go.

322
00:31:17,340 --> 00:31:21,984
And then when there's an equanimity, when the fear has subsided,

323
00:31:22,471 --> 00:31:25,295
then of course you see the situation with much more clarity.

324
00:31:25,895 --> 00:31:37,813
It doesn't mean to say that you can't see that unfortunate things may happen, but at least it takes away the huge agitation around it, the exaggeration of it.

325
00:31:39,895 --> 00:31:48,208
So that's the power of your mindfulness, you see, not to get caught up in thoughts driven by unwholesome mental states.

326
00:31:49,336 --> 00:31:56,083
And you'll do that when we do that, when we realize that, when we allow the mind to do that, it gets worse.

327
00:31:56,103 --> 00:31:57,825
It's actually developing the mental state.

328
00:32:00,968 --> 00:32:15,603
So, on a, shall we say, a very obvious psychological level, what mindfulness is doing is it's putting this awareness, this mindfulness, which is our intuitive intelligence.

329
00:32:16,663 --> 00:32:19,106
You know, we talk about mindfulness, we talk about awareness,

330
00:32:19,390 --> 00:32:22,835
But remember that two words always come together in the Buddhist scripture.

331
00:32:23,135 --> 00:32:29,265
It's Sampajanusatima, which means an intuitive intelligence and awareness.

332
00:32:29,285 --> 00:32:34,393
To think of them as two things is really to look at the two sides of the same coin.

333
00:32:34,854 --> 00:32:38,720
We have it in our language when we say, if you look carefully, you'll see.

334
00:32:39,661 --> 00:32:42,224
So the see is the grasping of the situations.

335
00:32:42,778 --> 00:32:53,057
So awareness is the ability to look dispassionately, to look from a position to an objective position, and as we look, we grasp the situation, we see what's wrong.

336
00:32:54,419 --> 00:33:00,990
So although we say this awareness and intuitive intelligence, it's actually intuitive awareness.

337
00:33:02,073 --> 00:33:06,339
And that's the reason I call this center satipañña, because that is the Buddha mind.

338
00:33:06,808 --> 00:33:14,037
See, to be in that state, you're in, you know, you're actually in a state of awakening, right?

339
00:33:14,057 --> 00:33:18,741
You can't say awakened, but we can say definitely a state of awakening, see?

340
00:33:18,761 --> 00:33:27,872
So, when we see the power of that to stop us making things worse and to undermine old habits, that's the point.

341
00:33:29,032 --> 00:33:34,960
When these mental states come up, remember, these are conditioning, they're old habits.

342
00:33:35,429 --> 00:33:43,582
And when we're undermining, when we're allowing them to manifest, we're actually allowing that turbulence to exhaust itself.

343
00:33:44,041 --> 00:33:45,163
So that's the healing.

344
00:33:45,203 --> 00:33:50,952
So these turbulences find it harder and harder to hijack our lives.

345
00:33:51,693 --> 00:33:59,866
We can stay above them, walk with them, see them as our companions, you see, but also to

346
00:34:00,303 --> 00:34:26,664
to turn a certain kindness towards them too as if you were with somebody who was depressed or anxious so this awareness this mindfulness can be saturated you might say or flavoured with loving kindness and that gives us a great strength it gives us a great courage to stay with the actual state no matter how long it stays see and

347
00:34:26,981 --> 00:34:56,601
it's through that process so it's through that process that two things are happening one is the psychological dis-ease is being eased and the other one is there's a slow recognition of where the escape is from all suffering by not by non-indulgence non-reactivity non-aversion non-fear see and it's seeing that second arrow as the Buddha would call it second dart of aversion

348
00:34:56,952 --> 00:35:26,452
fear pushing away you see and just allowing that to manifest and die away that we are slowly receding backwards to this place of of pure equanimity of non-reactivity so it could be you know in my understanding it could be that somebody who you know comes into therapy

349
00:35:26,786 --> 00:35:56,456
a mindfulness-based therapy I very easily just by observing the process of how suffering is created find their way to complete liberation on one of the insights as you do that of course the other two insights the other two characteristics of existence become obvious to the person as they move along for start they realize that

350
00:35:56,960 --> 00:36:00,043
everything is impermanent because they're watching it.

351
00:36:00,525 --> 00:36:04,190
So it dawns upon them that there's nothing that they're experiencing which remains.

352
00:36:04,851 --> 00:36:06,233
Nothing that is permanent.

353
00:36:06,253 --> 00:36:10,097
Therefore, everything that we experience is unreliable.

354
00:36:10,798 --> 00:36:11,599
You can't rely on it.

355
00:36:12,922 --> 00:36:16,126
You can't rely on a relationship lasting.

356
00:36:16,407 --> 00:36:21,373
I mean, the person might, you know, think better of it and off off.

357
00:36:21,393 --> 00:36:22,474
Or they die, you see.

358
00:36:22,514 --> 00:36:23,936
You can't rely on human beings.

359
00:36:23,956 --> 00:36:24,297
It's terrible.

360
00:36:24,318 --> 00:36:24,637
It's terrible.

361
00:36:25,309 --> 00:36:27,391
You can't rely on your happiness on another human being.

362
00:36:27,652 --> 00:36:28,652
You're into a hell realm.

363
00:36:30,054 --> 00:36:31,355
Because you're not in control.

364
00:36:31,414 --> 00:36:34,597
The whole point about being happy is that you're in control.

365
00:36:34,637 --> 00:36:39,463
And if you can't control something, there's always going to be fear that you'll lose control.

366
00:36:39,523 --> 00:36:44,206
So this is your attachment coming from this position of I am.

367
00:36:44,766 --> 00:36:46,909
I am a human being.

368
00:36:47,289 --> 00:36:50,753
As soon as you say I am a human being, you're stuck, you see.

369
00:36:51,793 --> 00:36:54,456
Because now you've got to seek perfect happiness in this form.

370
00:36:55,567 --> 00:37:01,492
And so you're constantly in conflict with the world because it just doesn't deliver.

371
00:37:04,396 --> 00:37:10,181
And that impermanence, you know, it leads you to this beautiful statement by the Buddha.

372
00:37:10,382 --> 00:37:13,246
You see, there's nothing in the world worth holding on to.

373
00:37:15,807 --> 00:37:22,956
And one thing you can do with these phrases when you come across them in a book that you're reading and it sort of strikes you is to keep repeating them, you know.

374
00:37:23,096 --> 00:37:23,936
This is the...

375
00:37:24,742 --> 00:37:28,086
This is the spiritual reading.

376
00:37:28,768 --> 00:37:30,969
So you come across a phase and you keep repeating it.

377
00:37:31,170 --> 00:37:31,951
Keep repeating it.

378
00:37:32,291 --> 00:37:34,094
Repeating it in all its inflections.

379
00:37:34,693 --> 00:37:38,358
Like there is nothing in the world worth holding on to.

380
00:37:38,398 --> 00:37:39,260
See?

381
00:37:39,280 --> 00:37:42,382
There is nothing in the world worth holding on to.

382
00:37:42,402 --> 00:37:45,686
There is nothing in the world worth holding on to.

383
00:37:45,726 --> 00:37:46,507
See?

384
00:37:46,527 --> 00:37:48,990
There is nothing in the world worth holding on to.

385
00:37:49,010 --> 00:37:49,090
See?

386
00:37:49,851 --> 00:37:51,813
And you keep repeating it and repeating it.

387
00:37:52,552 --> 00:37:55,416
And you repeat it gently until you feel a sort of digestion.

388
00:37:56,056 --> 00:38:00,442
And that means that it's moved from being an intellectual understanding into a disposition.

389
00:38:00,663 --> 00:38:02,385
It's moving into a disposition.

390
00:38:02,405 --> 00:38:07,971
And when that's really grasped, it comes out in your actions, in your speech, you see.

391
00:38:08,010 --> 00:38:09,873
That's your eightfold path, you see.

392
00:38:10,293 --> 00:38:13,217
If it stays at an intellectual level, it's sterile.

393
00:38:13,378 --> 00:38:14,719
Nothing's ever going to happen.

394
00:38:14,778 --> 00:38:18,284
You're going to sound very clever, but nothing's ever going to happen.

395
00:38:18,543 --> 00:38:22,088
It's got to move into the heart, you see, as a disposition.

396
00:38:24,210 --> 00:38:28,094
So, one sees this impermanence, you see.

397
00:38:28,114 --> 00:38:34,039
In seeing the world as impermanent, one begins to realize what is permanent within the world.

398
00:38:36,161 --> 00:38:45,088
So, these qualities, these characteristics are always making us find the opposites.

399
00:38:45,949 --> 00:38:53,255
So, where the Buddha says this is suffering, he talks about this place, for want of a better word, nibbana, where there is no suffering.

400
00:38:53,489 --> 00:39:22,449
don't call it happiness just says there's no suffering because if you say happiness we immediately associate that with some sort of emotional state see so he prefers the word no suffering and what is able to see that which arises and passes away must itself not be arising and passing away so another quality of Nibbana is that it's not transient it's not it's not it's not changing

401
00:39:22,717 --> 00:39:47,592
it's a state which has a permanency about it and is utterly reliable that's what he's saying and then as you begin to take this position of the observer two things become more plain to you is that your control over your body, heart and mind is only apparent so

402
00:39:48,028 --> 00:40:15,217
You can move your body around here and there but there's very little you can do about about your bones You know like I see whatever skeleton you've got you stuck with it, and you can you can get rid of bits of it No break bits of it, but but basically speaking So much of our of our physical nature is is a given isn't it I mean we don't even know what's happening doing we don't know what I mean do we know what's happening now in our liver and

403
00:40:16,092 --> 00:40:18,795
Yeah, completely blank as far as I'm concerned.

404
00:40:19,235 --> 00:40:21,880
And as long as it doesn't hurt, I'm quite happy to leave it alone.

405
00:40:23,322 --> 00:40:25,525
It's like neurobiology, you see.

406
00:40:25,545 --> 00:40:28,429
It tells about all these chemicals and neurons.

407
00:40:29,230 --> 00:40:30,210
I don't experience any of that.

408
00:40:31,413 --> 00:40:32,273
I haven't a clue what's going on.

409
00:40:33,054 --> 00:40:41,867
All I know is that I have these thoughts and images coming up here and I'm aware of feelings and emotions.

410
00:40:42,507 --> 00:40:44,309
So my actual experience of life

411
00:40:44,695 --> 00:40:48,320
It's nothing to do with chemicals and whatnot.

412
00:40:48,340 --> 00:40:51,143
Not to say that chemicals don't affect the experience of my life.

413
00:40:51,764 --> 00:40:54,007
But that's not what I actually experience, you see.

414
00:40:54,547 --> 00:40:59,092
So in thought, you see, what happens if we become senile?

415
00:40:59,112 --> 00:41:00,394
We suffer from Alzheimer's.

416
00:41:00,454 --> 00:41:01,456
Who are we then, you see?

417
00:41:03,438 --> 00:41:13,251
So this business of pulling out of and looking at something makes us realize, and it's a frightening thing, to realize that actually you're not in control.

418
00:41:15,255 --> 00:41:43,170
but it's also beginning to discover a position which is outside it so this is the transcendent position the transcendent position in its absoluteness cannot know itself if it knows itself then it must have an object if it's an object then it can't be it simple as that whatever is an object to awareness can't be the awareness it's an object so

419
00:41:44,163 --> 00:42:06,306
that's why the Buddha says even Nibbāna doesn't have this sense of self and that's the process of liberation the process of liberation is the eventual abandonment and destruction of any idea of a self that's all there is to it now when we

420
00:42:06,742 --> 00:42:15,349
As we experience, these things are not, they don't have to be mind-blowing, you know, like usually explosive sort of experiences.

421
00:42:16,070 --> 00:42:17,751
They're sometimes like a drip feed.

422
00:42:18,251 --> 00:42:25,237
And over a period of time, you sort of wake up and realize actually that you don't see the world as you did 5, 10, 15 years ago.

423
00:42:26,159 --> 00:42:28,019
Because it's sort of a slow dawning.

424
00:42:28,081 --> 00:42:32,204
That's why the word awakening is so much better than enlightenment, you know.

425
00:42:34,666 --> 00:42:35,567
And...

426
00:42:37,639 --> 00:42:43,306
as you begin to have that, as you begin to, as it were, find this identity, remember that it doesn't stop there.

427
00:42:43,326 --> 00:42:46,829
You have to re-enter the psychophysical organism.

428
00:42:47,449 --> 00:42:50,072
You have to become a person.

429
00:42:50,974 --> 00:42:56,440
And it's through the personhood that you begin to express the wisdom that you have.

430
00:42:57,081 --> 00:43:02,025
So, in the Buddha's own story, he retreats from life.

431
00:43:02,346 --> 00:43:05,168
He goes into these meditative experiences.

432
00:43:06,010 --> 00:43:06,650
And when he's

433
00:43:06,934 --> 00:43:14,505
fully, when he wakes up to what he's actually discovered, see, his first thought is, who can I share this with?

434
00:43:14,545 --> 00:43:15,126
Who can I teach?

435
00:43:15,967 --> 00:43:16,146
See?

436
00:43:16,768 --> 00:43:18,429
It's a sort of a natural outflow.

437
00:43:18,769 --> 00:43:28,543
So this Eightfold Path that he left, right understanding, right attitude, flows naturally into right speech, right action, and right livelihood.

438
00:43:29,704 --> 00:43:30,324
Right livelihood.

439
00:43:31,385 --> 00:43:36,552
And that's the way that you begin to understand that this...

440
00:43:36,853 --> 00:43:55,003
This process of mindfulness is actually making you re-engage in life in a much fuller way because it's not being enclosed by a barrier that we call the self.

441
00:43:55,503 --> 00:43:59,570
The self is always defining the world for its own self-benefit.

442
00:44:00,715 --> 00:44:06,963
And therefore the relationship we have with everybody or anything always has this angle of what's in it for me.

443
00:44:07,684 --> 00:44:08,485
See?

444
00:44:08,505 --> 00:44:12,090
When the what's in it for me goes, then you get that pure relationship.

445
00:44:12,711 --> 00:44:14,755
Not that there isn't anything in it for you.

446
00:44:15,175 --> 00:44:17,978
It's just that that's not the dominant thought.

447
00:44:17,998 --> 00:44:19,181
That's not become a barrier.

448
00:44:19,561 --> 00:44:22,164
It may be a boundary, but you can step over boundaries.

449
00:44:22,885 --> 00:44:25,369
But barriers, you can't step over.

450
00:44:25,389 --> 00:44:28,733
See?

451
00:44:28,753 --> 00:44:30,215
So...

452
00:44:30,635 --> 00:44:51,239
You can see how somebody who has entered into a therapy just with the purpose of overcoming panic or grief, they've had a terrible grief in their lives, and they're taught this business of separating the grief from this indulgence.

453
00:44:51,278 --> 00:44:59,527
So often when people die and we're left with this grief, we make the mistake of thinking that the amount of grief I have is the measure of my love.

454
00:45:00,519 --> 00:45:03,583
So that means that every time your grief begins to disappear, you panic.

455
00:45:04,304 --> 00:45:07,028
And you've got to start grieving because you're saying to yourself, I don't love this person anymore.

456
00:45:07,469 --> 00:45:08,351
So you have to grieve again.

457
00:45:09,373 --> 00:45:10,134
And so it goes on and on.

458
00:45:10,173 --> 00:45:14,199
It becomes a sort of a never-ending sort of indulgence in grief.

459
00:45:14,219 --> 00:45:20,469
And there's a sort of a deep satisfaction that, oh, I'm so grieving that I'm so happy that I love this person so much.

460
00:45:20,929 --> 00:45:23,672
But the grief is actually an expression of your attachment.

461
00:45:23,693 --> 00:45:25,195
Real love allows the person to go on.

462
00:45:25,856 --> 00:45:29,581
It's like, say, a parent who won't let the child go on.

463
00:45:30,001 --> 00:45:31,422
You're holding on to the child.

464
00:45:31,442 --> 00:45:41,492
But when the child is launched into the world, there should be happiness, you know, as well as relief.

465
00:45:41,512 --> 00:45:42,673
There's more happiness out.

466
00:45:42,693 --> 00:45:46,958
So it's like you see, you know, parents sees their children and they're happy for them.

467
00:45:46,978 --> 00:45:48,059
They don't hold on to them.

468
00:45:48,079 --> 00:45:52,603
They stay here, you know.

469
00:45:53,103 --> 00:45:57,307
So when a person sees, you see, when a person sees that grief,

470
00:45:58,434 --> 00:46:01,840
It's something coming out of attachment and allows the grief to pass.

471
00:46:01,860 --> 00:46:02,840
Stop indulging in it.

472
00:46:02,860 --> 00:46:18,521
Stop confusing it with love and allowing the person who's passed away to actually pass away and to rejoice in the relationship they had and just to let go of that person, let them go.

473
00:46:18,561 --> 00:46:20,583
Then, of course, the grief disappears.

474
00:46:21,065 --> 00:46:22,586
The grief begins to just exhaust itself.

475
00:46:23,056 --> 00:46:27,882
So it's not as though the mindfulness is going to help you get over the grief quicker.

476
00:46:28,222 --> 00:46:31,648
The process of grief will be determined by the measure of your attachment.

477
00:46:32,228 --> 00:46:34,492
But it's still going to take three, six, nine months.

478
00:46:35,152 --> 00:46:37,436
They say if it goes on longer than that, it's becoming chronic.

479
00:46:37,996 --> 00:46:42,202
But if you... You see, it doesn't stop the suffering.

480
00:46:42,242 --> 00:46:44,085
What it does is it opens you up to it.

481
00:46:44,485 --> 00:46:46,909
But it opens you up in a way that it's going to heal the heart.

482
00:46:47,650 --> 00:46:48,170
See?

483
00:46:48,190 --> 00:46:49,231
So you can see by...

484
00:46:49,938 --> 00:46:58,827
by seeing grief, supposing something comes with grief, and they cut in between this business of indulging grief from a wrong understanding that it's an expression of love.

485
00:46:59,547 --> 00:47:05,614
So this misunderstanding dies away, and the reaction of indulging grief therefore stops.

486
00:47:06,034 --> 00:47:11,981
The grief now is allowed to arise and pass away, and they're beginning to see that it's impermanent.

487
00:47:13,762 --> 00:47:15,405
And then they're beginning to see that actually,

488
00:47:15,806 --> 00:47:20,632
I'm looking at it, I'm feeling it, it's not me, even if it's only a slight insight.

489
00:47:20,974 --> 00:47:26,501
So all the time they're discovering this new identity of being the one who knows.

490
00:47:27,663 --> 00:47:41,780
So it seems to me that even though a person might enter at the level of deep suffering, of psychological suffering, there's a great possibility that they find their way completely.

491
00:47:46,030 --> 00:47:51,637
As the scripture says, in no length of time, so and so, so and so, became fully liberated.

492
00:47:53,199 --> 00:47:58,748
And the commentaries gloss that with 25 years in the forest.

493
00:47:58,768 --> 00:48:01,693
50 years in the forest, but in no length of time.

494
00:48:01,873 --> 00:48:03,996
Well, cosmically speaking, that's 25 years.

495
00:48:07,882 --> 00:48:12,929
Are there any questions around that?

496
00:48:13,028 --> 00:48:15,092
Banti, a lot of what you were saying

497
00:48:15,358 --> 00:48:44,775
related to experience of time impermanence and passing of things and so on I wonder if you could say a little bit more about the kind of Buddhist experience of time and the importance of the present because there's very much an idea of letting go of the past not becoming too involved in the future and also in a more

498
00:48:45,076 --> 00:48:48,802
In a more deep sense, there's an underlying picture of what reality is.

499
00:48:49,682 --> 00:48:53,027
It's saying, in a sense, there is no past and future.

500
00:48:53,068 --> 00:48:55,731
They aren't sort of solid, real things at all.

501
00:48:55,771 --> 00:48:59,697
And that's something that can be quite disturbing.

502
00:49:07,210 --> 00:49:14,019
Well, the mind is very clever, isn't it, in maintaining a certain continuity for us.

503
00:49:14,286 --> 00:49:25,277
And in a sense, it'd be difficult to see how you could operate without some level of continuity as to who you are, where your position was in society, what your job was.

504
00:49:25,757 --> 00:49:28,840
You've got to be in the morning and thought, I'm not supposed to be doing today.

505
00:49:30,121 --> 00:49:32,362
You have to ring around and find out, oh yeah, I'm supposed to be at work.

506
00:49:32,822 --> 00:49:36,927
So there has to be some connection to the past.

507
00:49:38,969 --> 00:49:42,572
You have to have known, it puts you in a position of,

508
00:49:42,907 --> 00:49:44,929
of time in flux.

509
00:49:47,931 --> 00:49:53,197
And time in flux is basically a series of events, isn't it?

510
00:49:53,217 --> 00:49:56,780
And you're slotted into that series.

511
00:49:58,081 --> 00:50:03,086
And there's a presumption it's going onwards.

512
00:50:03,106 --> 00:50:09,293
Remember that in the West we have this impression that time is linear, it's going somewhere, it has some sort of progress.

513
00:50:09,813 --> 00:50:12,896
Whereas in the East and in more ancient cultures

514
00:50:13,096 --> 00:50:14,097
It was more circular.

515
00:50:14,257 --> 00:50:15,619
It was just going round on itself.

516
00:50:17,501 --> 00:50:27,735
That's why in the West we often find it very difficult to think of rebirth or reincarnation because we have this idea of progress as a linear state.

517
00:50:28,016 --> 00:50:29,858
You begin here and you end up somewhere up there.

518
00:50:30,539 --> 00:50:41,414
But as I say, the more sort of circular idea of time which you find in the East allows the mind to

519
00:50:41,733 --> 00:50:50,423
allows us to create the possibility that things come round again, things come round again.

520
00:50:51,425 --> 00:50:58,074
So... And in daily life, you have to know.

521
00:50:58,114 --> 00:51:04,722
I mean, if you've got a dental appointment on Monday, you have to reorganise yourself for that dental appointment.

522
00:51:04,742 --> 00:51:10,170
So you can't lose a reality base of what's actually happening at the level of,

523
00:51:10,724 --> 00:51:14,467
where you are in society, what you're supposed to be doing, where you're supposed to be going, and so on.

524
00:51:14,648 --> 00:51:15,367
That's right.

525
00:51:16,048 --> 00:51:27,099
But, of course, the delusion is that this is something that has an absolute reality about it.

526
00:51:30,543 --> 00:51:34,447
If you walk into a door, there's something absolutely real about that.

527
00:51:35,268 --> 00:51:35,967
You know what I mean?

528
00:51:36,588 --> 00:51:39,751
It's solid, and it's there, and you've hurt yourself, see?

529
00:51:40,255 --> 00:51:45,081
But we know that actually it's just subatomic particles meeting subatomic particles.

530
00:51:45,922 --> 00:51:52,869
I mean, there's another level of reality, you can say, that there's actually not much there apart from this energy.

531
00:51:52,969 --> 00:51:54,431
This is what we are told.

532
00:51:54,552 --> 00:51:56,715
I've never experienced that myself.

533
00:51:56,735 --> 00:52:01,860
But this is what we're told, that there's this level of reality about the universe we're living in, which is just energy.

534
00:52:01,960 --> 00:52:04,244
It's just this frazzled energy.

535
00:52:05,485 --> 00:52:06,887
So...

536
00:52:07,188 --> 00:52:12,795
In the belief of continuity, in that sense, there's a belief, an underlying belief, that it's the same person.

537
00:52:13,576 --> 00:52:15,318
That's where the delusion is.

538
00:52:15,338 --> 00:52:25,731
So, even though you see that your face has changed since you were a child, even in the last five, ten years, you still say, well, it's me.

539
00:52:26,130 --> 00:52:26,871
That's me, you see.

540
00:52:27,733 --> 00:52:34,360
There's something in us which remains this insoluble, permanent sense of I-ness, of me-ness.

541
00:52:35,623 --> 00:52:35,742
See?

542
00:52:36,179 --> 00:52:43,525
even though all our opinions have changed over a certain lifetime, there's still me that hasn't changed.

543
00:52:44,666 --> 00:52:49,030
Even though all my emotions are constantly changing and moving around, I don't change.

544
00:52:49,672 --> 00:52:51,594
See, this sense of I, see?

545
00:52:51,614 --> 00:53:01,943
And this sense of I creates a permanency dependent on this impermanent relationship, on this impermanent happening in our lives.

546
00:53:02,284 --> 00:53:04,565
So it's I that I'm going to the dentist.

547
00:53:05,018 --> 00:53:06,320
It's I that I'm thinking.

548
00:53:06,519 --> 00:53:08,222
It's I that I'm doing this.

549
00:53:08,503 --> 00:53:12,268
And this I, you see, substantiates the present moment.

550
00:53:12,869 --> 00:53:14,431
Turns it into a real thing.

551
00:53:14,472 --> 00:53:31,295
Now, when you bring your attention to the present moment, into the here and now, you'll hear that, you know, you read that in the literature, you are able to

552
00:53:31,715 --> 00:53:34,639
stop this growth of I.

553
00:53:35,099 --> 00:53:41,748
So this is the other problem with this fundamental delusion of this becoming.

554
00:53:42,851 --> 00:53:50,121
By always in a state of becoming, it's a way that we feel we can control the future.

555
00:53:51,242 --> 00:53:52,985
So you're going to do this.

556
00:53:53,005 --> 00:53:56,009
I'm going on holiday to this sort of place.

557
00:53:56,048 --> 00:53:57,992
When I retire...

558
00:53:58,309 --> 00:54:01,835
And it makes you feel very safe because you've got it all worked out.

559
00:54:02,755 --> 00:54:04,998
The rest of the world doesn't know you've got it all worked out.

560
00:54:05,039 --> 00:54:05,760
This is the problem.

561
00:54:06,300 --> 00:54:07,983
It's only you know that it's got it worked out.

562
00:54:08,322 --> 00:54:12,768
So this sense of I, you see, begins to collapse.

563
00:54:12,809 --> 00:54:13,909
It begins to move.

564
00:54:13,969 --> 00:54:26,786
As you move into the present moment, you see, and see the present moment in its totality, you're aware of the difference of the next moment and that it's arising dependent on and yet separate from this present moment.

565
00:54:27,407 --> 00:54:27,507
See?

566
00:54:27,527 --> 00:54:27,608
See?

567
00:54:27,976 --> 00:54:39,990
So there's a feeling of letting go of that grasping onto time, onto this present, onto a future which you can only imagine.

568
00:54:40,110 --> 00:54:41,291
It doesn't actually exist.

569
00:54:41,952 --> 00:54:44,396
The future cannot exist, but you imagine it.

570
00:54:45,217 --> 00:54:56,751
And what it does is it opens you up to the present moment in a way that allows the potential of that present moment and its expression to be much more available.

571
00:54:57,742 --> 00:55:17,262
So if, for instance, your sense of control is about the sort of person you like, if you go through all your friends, you'll notice that you like them all.

572
00:55:18,244 --> 00:55:18,925
See, that's one of the...

573
00:55:20,001 --> 00:55:22,545
If you go through all your enemies, you'll notice that you don't like them.

574
00:55:22,885 --> 00:55:26,710
So you've split the world into all these people whom you like.

575
00:55:26,789 --> 00:55:34,460
Now, every time you form a friendship, you reinforce this idea of who you like.

576
00:55:35,141 --> 00:55:42,809
And without you knowing it, you've put blinkers on because you've defined what is likeable, and what's likeable is what's likeable to you.

577
00:55:44,692 --> 00:55:48,556
Now, if you're in the present moment much more,

578
00:55:48,757 --> 00:56:12,250
and you're open to a new person coming towards you and you haven't got this history of what I like and what I don't like and you're completely open and you're not envisaging some sort of friendship out of this then as you meet this person you're much more open to them and your sense of who you like and what you don't like begins to expand much more at ease

579
00:56:13,175 --> 00:56:20,342
So this whole business of time in Buddhist understanding, it's a mental construct.

580
00:56:20,422 --> 00:56:24,766
It doesn't actually exist, and I think most people would see that fairly clearly.

581
00:56:25,527 --> 00:56:40,222
And we're in a vortex of actions and reactions, and what awareness is trying to do is to weave a way through that which is going to create happiness.

582
00:56:41,643 --> 00:56:41,764
See?

583
00:56:47,650 --> 00:56:48,311
Does that make sense?

584
00:56:51,875 --> 00:57:02,347
So we're in this sort of state of being in time flux, but the awareness is absolutely now within the flux.

585
00:57:03,548 --> 00:57:10,077
It's not allowing itself to build up a future from what's happening now because it knows it doesn't know what the future is.

586
00:57:11,099 --> 00:57:17,286
In not knowing the future, it then, as the next moment comes up, is completely open to it because it's not trying to manipulate it.

587
00:57:19,612 --> 00:57:49,112
and in not trying to manipulate something one sees the fullness of it yeah when one sees the fullness of it one sees the potential of it and in seeing the fullness of the potential of it one hopes that the decision made is going to produce something greater out of that situation I think I'm sure everybody here has experienced the point in their lives when

588
00:57:49,514 --> 00:57:51,297
you come to a sort of full stop.

589
00:57:53,559 --> 00:57:54,641
And you don't know what to do.

590
00:57:55,262 --> 00:58:01,351
And in that sort of emptiness of not knowing what to do, where to go, there is a certain type of openness there.

591
00:58:02,793 --> 00:58:04,275
And then something always arises.

592
00:58:04,936 --> 00:58:12,186
Especially if you have a general aspiration, you know, a generalized aspiration to be involved in something.

593
00:58:13,487 --> 00:58:13,728
Yeah?

594
00:58:14,009 --> 00:58:14,650
Or is that just me?

595
00:58:16,733 --> 00:58:16,972
Gosh.

596
00:58:19,601 --> 00:58:20,161
Yeah, you see.

597
00:58:21,143 --> 00:58:22,344
It's being able to...

598
00:58:23,726 --> 00:58:33,193
It's stopping presumptions from the past launching into the future and creating what we think is something real.

599
00:58:34,635 --> 00:58:40,440
And when something comes against that projection that we've made, we're always in conflict.

600
00:58:40,760 --> 00:58:41,621
We're in conflict with it.

601
00:58:45,103 --> 00:58:48,646
And if it happens to conjoin with our projection...

602
00:58:49,166 --> 00:58:54,532
will drive it to its bitter end because we don't see its consequences.

603
00:58:55,012 --> 00:58:59,818
I mean, an obvious example is this financial crash.

604
00:59:00,318 --> 00:59:04,601
Who was the last Treasury guy in the States?

605
00:59:05,043 --> 00:59:06,204
The one with the glasses.

606
00:59:07,985 --> 00:59:09,507
Do you know who I mean?

607
00:59:10,728 --> 00:59:11,509
Names evade me.

608
00:59:11,668 --> 00:59:13,331
I suffer from nominal aphasia.

609
00:59:15,233 --> 00:59:16,474
Yes, green space.

610
00:59:17,887 --> 00:59:26,936
He said, didn't he, he said it was just greed, that nobody foresaw that the whole thing would collapse because they were still stuck in this greed.

611
00:59:27,438 --> 00:59:29,420
That's a wonderful example of what happens.

612
00:59:30,360 --> 00:59:32,543
You don't think things are going to end because you keep projecting.

613
00:59:32,603 --> 00:59:33,264
It can't end.

614
00:59:33,284 --> 00:59:37,288
This is always going to be this tremendous growth of wealth.

615
00:59:38,007 --> 00:59:38,889
They just don't see it coming.

616
00:59:39,469 --> 00:59:45,556
And the Queen writes to all these economists at the London School of Economics and says, why didn't anybody see this?

617
00:59:45,576 --> 00:59:46,376
Because they're all greedy.

618
00:59:48,331 --> 00:59:50,293
It's a tunnel vision, isn't it?

619
00:59:53,016 --> 01:00:01,385
Very few people foresaw this collapse coming.

620
01:00:01,405 --> 01:00:02,927
But it's interesting, isn't it?

621
01:00:02,947 --> 01:00:08,313
We have such a different way of thinking about the future than thinking about the past.

622
01:00:08,353 --> 01:00:14,221
So we think the future is completely open and undetermined and not there in a way.

623
01:00:14,240 --> 01:00:14,862
We make it.

624
01:00:15,532 --> 01:00:20,739
And we think the past is all fixed and definite and that it's an absolute reality.

